{
  "texts": [
    "Further, no significant usage change were found from level 4 to level 5 across degree expressions subtypes, suggesting that degree expressions learnability manifests at a relatively early learning stage, and it becomes less evident as learners arrive at the advanced stage.",
    "We found random effects for all the four aforementioned models, suggesting that there are individual differences in the usage of degree expressions.",
    "We additionally visualized the usage percentage of each degree expression subtype in a stacked bar plot (Figure 3).",
    "Aside from the shrinkage of explicit phrasal comparatives and -er comparatives usage and the corresponding expansion of implicit comparatives and more/less comparatives, Figure 3 illustrated that, as predicted, clausal comparatives are rarely used across L2 learners' interlanguage development stages.",
    "Our finding also added new empirical evidence to the research on the Differential Markedness Hypothesis (Eckman, 1977)."
  ]
}